# C# Naming Conventions

## Names are full words — 1 to 4 words, no abbreviations or single letters

Names for fields, properties, variables, parameters, and methods must be full English words. Single-letter names and abbreviations are not allowed, except for established loop counters (`i`, `j`) inside a `for` body where the index has no domain meaning.

```csharp
// ❌ BAD
private Rigidbody rb;
private float spd;
float h = input.x;
void CalcVel() { }

// ✅ GOOD
private Rigidbody Body;
private float Speed;
float horizontal = input.x;
void CalculateVelocity() { }
```

## All members use PascalCase — no underscore prefix. Method members and consts use camelCase

```csharp
// ❌ BAD
private float _speed;
private Rigidbody _rb;
float Velociy = _speed;

// ✅ GOOD
private float Speed;
private Rigidbody Rigidbody;
float velocity = Speed;
```

## All methods use PascalCase (public and private)

```csharp
// ❌ BAD
private void handleMovement() { }
public void snapToGrid() { }

// ✅ GOOD
private void HandleMovement() { }
public void SnapToGrid() { }
```

## Braces on every clause — no single-line bodies

All control-flow statements (`if`, `else`, `for`, `foreach`, `while`, `do`, `switch`) must use `{ }`, even for a single line.

```csharp
// ❌ BAD
if (kb == null) return;
if (Head == null) Head = transform;

// ✅ GOOD
if (kb == null)
{
    return;
}

if (Head == null)
{
    Head = transform;
}
```

## No null checks for object references

Do **not** null-check object references. Assume all objects are correctly assigned and non-null. A `NullReferenceException` is the intended signal when something is misconfigured.

```csharp
// ❌ BAD
if (Data == null)
{
    return;
}
Data.DoSomething();

// ✅ GOOD
Data.DoSomething();
```

**Exceptions** — a null check is permitted only when explicitly noted inline with `// null-check: <reason>`.
